  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the places to visit in Chennai?",
  "response": "Chennai, the capital city of Tamil Nadu, is rich in culture, history, and natural beauty. Here are some popular places to visit in Chennai:\n\n1. **Marina Beach**: One of the longest urban beaches in the world, Marina Beach is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike. It\u2019s ideal for morning walks, evening strolls, and enjoying local snacks.\n\n2. **Kapaleeshwarar Temple**: A stunning example of Dravidian architecture, this ancient temple dedicated to Lord Shiva is located in Mylapore and is known for its beautiful gopuram (tower) and vibrant festivals.\n\n3. **Fort St. George**: Built in 1644, this fort marks the beginning of Chennai. It houses the St. Mary's Church, the oldest Anglican church in India, and a museum showcasing the city's colonial history.\n\n4. **Government Museum**: Located in Egmore, this museum is one of the oldest in India and features a vast collection of archaeological artifacts, fine arts, and natural history exhibits.\n\n5. **Theosophical Society**: Nestled in Adyar, this serene place is known for its lush gardens, the famous Adyar Banyan Tree, and the beautiful Blavatsky Bungalow.\n\n6. **Valluvar Kottam**: A memorial dedicated to the Tamil poet and philosopher Thiruvalluvar, it features a huge statue of the poet and an intricately carved chariot-shaped structure.\n\n7. **Santhome Cathedral Basilica**: This beautiful church, built over the tomb of St. Thomas, one of the twelve apostles of Jesus, is an architectural marvel and an important pilgrimage site.\n\n8. **Besant Nagar Beach**: A quieter alternative to Marina Beach, Besant Nagar Beach is popular for its relaxed atmosphere, eateries, and vibrant beach culture.\n\n9. **Mahabalipuram**: Located about an hour\u2019s drive from Chennai, this UNESCO World Heritage Site is known for its rock-cut temples and sculptures, including the famous Shore Temple.\n\n10. **Chennai Snake Park**: Located in the Adyar area, this park is dedicated to the conservation of snakes and other reptiles, providing an educational experience for visitors.\n\n11. **Birla Planetarium**: An interactive planetarium that offers shows and exhibitions related to astronomy and space science.\n\n12. **Pondy Bazaar**: A bustling shopping area that offers a variety of goods, from clothes to street food, it\u2019s a great place to experience the local shopping culture.\n\n13. **Guindy National Park**: A unique urban national park that provides a habitat for various species of flora and fauna, including deer and birds, and is a perfect spot for nature lovers.\n\n14. **Ekkatuthangal**: Known for the famous Sri Ramakrishna Math, it is a peaceful place with beautiful gardens and a serene atmosphere.\n\nThese attractions represent just a glimpse of what Chennai has to offer, blending modernity with rich traditions and history.",
